FILL_CH12 = {
  "12": {
    "1": "<p><strong>peri de tōn pneumatikōn</strong> (<em>peri de tōn pneumatikōn</em>): the phrase is grammatically ambiguous — the adjective <em>pneumatikōn</em> can be neuter plural ('spiritual things/gifts') or masculine plural ('spiritual persons'). The neuter reading suits the context better: Paul is addressing what spiritual gifts are and how they function. <em>Ou thelō hymas agnoein</em> (I do not want you to be ignorant) — a Pauline disclosure formula that signals an authoritative statement follows.</p>",
    "2": "<p><strong>ethnē ete pros ta eidōla ta aphōna hōs an ēgesthe apagomenoi</strong>: 'you were Gentiles, led away to mute idols however you were led.' <em>Aphōna</em> (mute/voiceless) ironically contrasts with the Spirit-speech Paul is about to discuss — idols cannot speak, the Spirit does. <em>Apagomenoi</em> (led away) is a passive participle of compulsion: the pagan past was characterized by being driven rather than led by God's Spirit.</p>",
    "3": "<p><strong>anathema Iēsous</strong> vs. <strong>kyrios Iēsous</strong>: the two confessional poles. <em>Anathema</em> = devoted to destruction, an LXX technical term for objects of divine curse (Deut 7:26). Whether 'Jesus be cursed' was a formula forced on believers under persecution or a Corinthian spiritual-pride claim ('the earthly Jesus is irrelevant, only the heavenly Christ matters') is debated. Either way, Paul's criterion is clear: the Spirit of God produces the confession of Jesus's lordship, never his cursing.</p>",
    "4": "<p><strong>diaireseis charismaton</strong> (<em>diaireseis charismaton</em>): <em>diairesis</em> = distribution or distinction/variety — the same Spirit distributes various gifts rather than one gift to all. <em>Charisma</em> (grace-gift, plural <em>charismata</em>) is Paul's own coinage built on <em>charis</em> (grace) — a gift whose basis is God's favor, not human merit or capacity. The three-verse structure (vv. 4-6) attributes the variety of gifts, services, and workings to the Spirit, Lord, and God respectively — an early Trinitarian-patterned statement.</p>",
    "5": "<p><strong>diaireseis diakoniōn</strong> (<em>diaireseis diakoniōn</em>): <em>diakonia</em> = service, ministry — the same word used for table-waiting (Acts 6:2) and apostolic ministry (2 Cor 6:3). Paul deliberately places 'service' as the second category of Spirit-distribution after 'gifts' — the charismata are not status-conferring trophies but service-functions within the community. <em>Ho autos kyrios</em> (the same Lord) — Christ is the source of the variety of ministry-forms.</p>",
    "6": "<p><strong>energēmata</strong> (<em>energēmata</em>): workings, operations — from <em>energeō</em> (to be at work, cf. English 'energy'). The third category: active divine workings that express the gifts and services. <em>Ho de autos Theos ho energōn ta panta en pasin</em> (the same God who works all things in all people) — the sovereignty of God over all pneumatic activity: what looks like human charismatic diversity is the unified working of one God through many persons.</p>",
    "7": "<p><strong>phanerōsis tou pneumatos</strong> (<em>phanerōsis tou pneumatos</em>): manifestation of the Spirit — <em>phanerōō</em> = to make visible/apparent. The individual gift is the Spirit's self-disclosure through the person; the gift is not owned by the receiver but is the Spirit appearing through them. <em>Pros to sympheron</em> (for the common good) — <em>sympheron</em> = advantage, benefit (same word as 6:12 and 10:23); the criterion for evaluating any exercise of a gift is its communal benefit.</p>",
    "8": "<p><strong>logos sophias / logos gnōseōs</strong>: 'utterance of wisdom / utterance of knowledge.' Both are <em>logos</em>-compounds: not wisdom or knowledge as possession but as speech-act, oral communication. In the Corinthian context where <em>sophia</em> (wisdom) was the premium currency (1:17-2:5), Paul democratizes it: wisdom comes as a Spirit-given utterance to specific persons for specific occasions, not as the general intellectual achievement of the <em>sophos</em>.</p>",
    "9": "<p><strong>pistis</strong> (faith, v. 9): distinct from saving faith — this is a special gift of faith for miraculous action (cf. 13:2: 'faith to move mountains'). <strong>Charismata iamatōn</strong> (gifts of healing): the plural of both <em>charisma</em> and <em>iama</em> (healing) is unusual — perhaps indicating multiple types of healing gifts or multiple instances, each a distinct grace-gift rather than a permanent endowment.</p>",
    "10": "<p><strong>energēmata dynameōn</strong> (workings of powers/miracles): the <em>dynamis</em> vocabulary for miraculous acts; <strong>diakrisis pneumatōn</strong> (discernment of spirits): <em>diakrisis</em> = judgment, distinguishing — evaluating which spirits/prophecies are genuinely from God (cf. 1 John 4:1). <strong>Genē glōssōn</strong> (kinds of tongues): <em>genē</em> = varieties/kinds, suggesting differentiation even within the tongue-gift. <strong>Hermēneia glōssōn</strong> (interpretation of tongues): the complementary gift enabling tongues to function as intelligible speech in the assembly.</p>",
    "11": "<p><strong>to hen kai to auto pneuma</strong> (the one and the same Spirit): <em>hen</em> and <em>auto</em> together emphatically assert unity — not merely one of a kind but numerically identical across all manifestations. <strong>Diairoun</strong> (distributing): the active participle of <em>diairō</em> = to divide and distribute — echoing <em>diairesis</em> in vv. 4-6. <strong>Kath' hekastō</strong> (to each one individually): the Spirit's distribution is personal and intentional, not random.</p>",
    "12": "<p><strong>houtōs kai ho Christos</strong> (so also Christ): the body-analogy's conclusion identifies the body not merely 'with the church' but with Christ himself — the body is Christ. This goes beyond illustration: the Corinthians' treatment of the body's members is their treatment of Christ's own body. The Christological intensity of the ecclesiology emerges here: harming the community is harming Christ (cf. 9:5: 'whom you are persecuting').</p>",
    "13": "<p><strong>en heni pneumati eis hen sōma ebaptisthēmen</strong> (in one Spirit we were all baptized into one body): the preposition <em>en</em> is instrumental ('by') or locative ('in') — either the Spirit is the agent or the sphere of baptism. <em>Eis hen sōma</em> (into one body) — baptism is not individual spiritual transaction but corporate incorporation. <strong>Eite Ioudaioi eite Hellēnes eite douloi eite eleutheroi</strong>: the social binary pairs (ethnic, legal) are transcended by the Spirit's baptism — the body is constituted across the deepest social divisions of the Roman world.</p>",
    "14": "<p><strong>to sōma ouk estin hen melos alla polla</strong> (the body is not one member but many): the premise for the following argument against gift-competition. The body's plurality is not a problem to overcome but the structural reality that makes the body a body. A one-member body is not a body at all — it is a monstrosity. Paul uses this anatomical truism to attack the Corinthian impulse to reduce the body's richness to a single valued gift (tongues).</p>",
    "15": "<p><strong>ean eipen ho pous</strong> (if the foot should say): the personified body-parts speak — the device allows Paul to give the gift-competition argument a reductio ad absurdum form. <em>Para touto ouk estin ek tou sōmatos</em> (on account of that it does not belong to the body) — the self-exclusion logic is exposed as incoherent: no body-part decides its own body-membership. The foot cannot disqualify itself by comparing itself unfavorably to the hand.</p>",
    "16": "<p><strong>ean eipen to ous</strong> (if the ear should say): the second personification, repeating the structure. The parallel body-part arguments (foot/hand, ear/eye) hit different audience members: those who feel excluded (foot/ear) and those who might exclude others (eye saying to the hand, v. 21). Both are anatomical absurdities that expose the absurdity of spiritual gift competition and dismissal.</p>",
    "17": "<p><strong>ei holon to sōma ophthalmos</strong> (if the whole body were an eye): the reductio from the body-pluralism argument. If the Corinthians got what they apparently wanted — everyone with the same gift (tongues being the most visible) — the 'body' would be a grotesque monstrosity, not a functioning organism. <em>Pou hē akoe</em> (where would the hearing be?); <em>pou hē osphrēsis</em> (where would the sense of smell be?) — the anatomy drives the ecclesiology.</p>",
    "18": "<p><strong>nun de ho Theos etheto ta melē hekastou autōn en tō sōmati kathōs ēthelésen</strong> (God has placed each member in the body as he chose): <em>etheto</em> (aorist of <em>tithēmi</em>, to place, appoint) — God's active arrangement of the body's diversity is a creation-level decision, not an accidental variation. <em>Kathōs ēthelésen</em> (as he chose) — the theological grounding: gift-distribution reflects divine sovereignty and intention, not spiritual achievement.</p>",
    "19": "<p><strong>ei de ēn ta panta hen melos</strong> (if all were one member): the hypothetical homogeneity argument continued. <em>Pou to sōma</em> (where would the body be?) — the body would cease to exist as a body. The argument proves from anatomy that unity requires diversity: a body of identical members is not a body but a mass of undifferentiated tissue. The Corinthians' preference for uniformity (all speak in tongues) would, paradoxically, destroy the very body they belong to.</p>",
    "20": "<p><strong>nun de polla men melē hen de sōma</strong> (many members but one body): the summary thesis of the body-analogy argument. The <em>men/de</em> construction (many... but one) holds the tension without collapsing either side. This is Paul's ecclesiological statement in its most compressed form: the community is one organism precisely because it is composed of diverse, non-interchangeable members. The unity is not uniformity.</p>",
    "21": "<p><strong>ou dynatai ho ophthalmos eipein tē cheiri chreia sou ouk echō</strong> (the eye cannot say to the hand 'I have no need of you'): the argument from an opposing direction — now the strong member cannot exclude the seemingly weaker one. <em>Ou dynatai</em> (cannot) — the impossibility is anatomical and theological. The body's interdependence is a structural feature, not a moral aspiration. The eye's apparent independence from the hand is an illusion of function-specialization, not independence of existence.</p>",
    "22": "<p><strong>ta dokounte asthenesteron hyparchein melē tou sōmatos anankaia estin</strong> (the members that seem weaker are indispensable): <em>asthenesteron</em> = weaker, more fragile (the comparative of <em>asthenēs</em>); <em>anankaia</em> = necessary, indispensable — the paradox that the apparently fragile members are the most necessary. This overturns the Corinthian honor-scale: the visible, dramatic gifts (tongues) are not more valuable than the apparently weaker ones (helps, administration).</p>",
    "23": "<p><strong>ta atimōtera tou sōmatos toutois timēn perissoteran peritheumen</strong> (on these we bestow greater honor): <em>atimotera</em> (less honored, comparative of <em>atimos</em>) vs. <em>perissoteran timēn</em> (greater honor) — the honor-reversal: human practice actually reinforces the body's care for less-honored members by clothing them more carefully. <em>Euschēmosynēn perissoteran echei</em> (has greater modesty) — the anatomy of clothing practices demonstrates the principle Paul wants for the church.</p>",
    "24": "<p><strong>ta de euschēmona hēmōn ou chreian echei</strong> (our presentable members have no need): <em>euschēmona</em> (well-formed, honorable) — the presentable, naturally dignified members need no additional honor. <strong>Synekrasen to sōma tō hysterountī perissoterēn dous timēn</strong> (God has blended the body together, giving greater honor to the lesser part): <em>synkeraō</em> = to mix together, blend — God is the one who deliberately constructs the body with this compensatory honor-distribution to the disadvantaged members.</p>",
    "25": "<p><strong>hina mē ē schisma en tō sōmati</strong> (so that there may be no division in the body): <em>schisma</em> = tear, division — the same word used for the community divisions in 1:10 and 11:18. The body-analogy's purpose is anti-schismatic: understanding the body's unity-in-diversity is the cure for factional gift-competition. <em>Merimnosōsin</em> (care for one another) — <em>merimnaō</em> = to be anxious about, to take care of; the mutual concern is the positive expression of the body's unity.</p>",
    "26": "<p><strong>ei pathei hen melos sympaschei panta ta melē</strong> (if one member suffers, all the members suffer together): <em>sympaschō</em> = to suffer together with (syn-compound) — the involuntary solidarity of a body that shares neural connection. <em>Syndoxazetai panta ta melē</em> (if one member is honored, all the members rejoice together) — <em>syndoxazō</em> = to be glorified together. The positive and negative solidarity are symmetrical: what happens to one happens to all. This is the theological basis for communal lament and communal celebration.</p>",
    "27": "<p><strong>hymeis de este sōma Christou kai melē ek merous</strong> (you are the body of Christ and individually members of it): the direct ecclesiological claim, no longer analogy. <em>Sōma Christou</em> (body of Christ) — the community is identified as Christ's body, not merely organized like a body. <em>Ek merous</em> (each in his part/individually) — each person is a member, not the whole. The corporate identification with Christ is total; the individual's position within it is partial and defined by relation to the whole.</p>",
    "28": "<p><strong>etheto ho Theos en tē ekklēsia prōton apostolous deuteron prophētas triton didaskalous</strong> (God has appointed in the church first apostles, second prophets, third teachers): <em>prōton... deuteron... triton</em> is a ranked sequence, then the list shifts to ungrouped items. <strong>Antilēmpseis</strong> (acts of helping) — a hapax in Paul, from <em>antilambanō</em> = to take hold, to help; the term may suggest supporting the weak. <strong>Kyberneseis</strong> (acts of guiding/administration) — from <em>kybernaō</em>, to pilot/steer a ship; used for governance and organizational leadership.</p>",
    "29": "<p><strong>mē pantes apostoloi</strong> (are all apostles?): the rhetorical <em>mē</em> expects a negative answer — 'not all are apostles, are they?' The sequence of seven rhetorical questions (vv. 29-30) demolishes any claim that one gift is universally distributed. <em>Mē pantes charismata echōsin iamatōn</em> (do all have gifts of healing?) — the negative answer to each question is the argument against the Corinthian elevation of any single gift as the mark of genuine spirituality.</p>",
    "30": "<p><strong>mē pantes glōssais lalousin</strong> (do all speak in tongues?): the question aimed directly at the Corinthian preference. The implied answer — 'of course not' — undermines the unstated claim that tongues is the spiritual gift that all genuine believers must manifest. <em>Mē pantes diermēneuousin</em> (do all interpret?) — the follow-up makes the point: the gift of tongues requires the paired gift of interpretation to be communally useful.</p>",
    "31": "<p><strong>zēloute de ta charismata ta meizona</strong> (eagerly desire the greater gifts): <em>zēloō</em> = to be zealous for, to eagerly pursue — the same verb will appear in 14:1, 39. The 'greater' gifts are those most beneficial for the community (prophecy over tongues, because prophecy is intelligible). <em>Kai eti kath' hyperbolēn hodon hymin deiknymi</em> (and I show you a still more excellent way) — <em>kath' hyperbolēn</em> = beyond all comparison, superabundantly; the transition to the love-chapter. Love is not a gift but the <em>way</em> in which all gifts must operate.</p>"
  }
}

